{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0bcb7c64-f7fe-4286-9155-b2c03b332afc","content":"## 2. Configure NuGet.org (manual step)\n\nOn **nuget.org**, register your GitHub repo as a trusted publisher:\n\n1. Go to [nuget.org](https://www.nuget.org) → **Manage Packages** → select your package (or set this up when first pushing)\n2. Navigate to **Trusted Publishers** → **Add Trusted Publisher**\n3. Fill in:\n   - **Repository owner:** `myorg`\n   - **Repository name:** `mylib`\n   - **Workflow filename:** `publish.yml`\n   - **Environment:** *(leave blank unless you use a GitHub environment)*\n\n## Key points\n\n- **`id-token: write`** permission is required — this lets the runner request an OIDC token.\n- **No API key needed** — NuGet verifies the token issued by GitHub's OIDC provider.\n- The workflow triggers on version tags (`v*`). Push a tag like `git tag v1.0.0 && git push --tags` to publish.\n- Make sure your `.csproj` has `<PackageId>`, `<Version>`, and other package metadata set.\n\nThe workflow file is at `.github/workflows/publish.yml` and is ready to commit.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"00d8f5d3-d088-4607-8c9e-8efc901d9550","outputTokens":292,"requestId":"FE0E:138350:137E400:15D0DE6:6A066E94"},"id":"c6897f1e-1ec2-46a7-b7de-8321b936f7d5","timestamp":"2026-05-15T00:53:50.492Z","parentId":"d21d571d-b9fb-479a-8a5a-8db4a7a4a2cf"}
